{% block content %}
  <div class="content-note">This page covers the toxic-drug crisis and overdose response, without stigma.</div>

  <h2>Naloxone saves lives</h2>
  <p>Naloxone reverses an opioid overdose. Free kits are available in Ontario at participating pharmacies, with no prescription or health card needed, and through community organizations and Indigenous health services, and First Nations clients can get kits free through Non-Insured Health Benefits. If you see an overdose, call 911, give naloxone, and stay. Ontario's Good Samaritan law gives some legal protection to people who call for help.</p>

  <h2>Culturally safe support</h2>
  <p>The Thunderbird Partnership Foundation leads First Nations harm reduction in a wholistic, culturally grounded, non-stigmatizing way. Locally, Maamwesying's Minobimaadizing program offers addictions support, same-day treatment options, and naloxone, and Gwekwaadziwin Miikan on Manitoulin offers land-based youth and young-adult treatment.</p>

  <h2>Talk to someone</h2>
  <p>Hope for Wellness, 1-855-242-3310, and Talk4Healing, 1-855-554-4325, are there 24/7. ConnexOntario, 1-866-531-2600, helps you find mental-health and addictions services.</p>

